Package gw.api.webservice.exception

  • Class Summary 
    Class Description
    AlreadyExecutedException
    BadIdentifierException
    Thrown when an internal public ID doesn't map to a real bean (problem could be that type was incorrect).
    BatchProcessException
    SOAP Exception specific to batch process operations
    DataConversionException
    Thrown by many APIs when they encounter a problem translating a SOAP data object into an internal system object.
    DuplicateKeyException
    Throws if a duplicate data exception is detected in the database. I.e. a unique index violation.
    EntityStateException
    Thrown when an attempt is made to manipulate an object that is in a state that prevents the operation from being performed. An example is trying to modify a Claim that is marked as closed.
    FieldConversionException
    Thrown when a data type cannot be converted into the native data type.
    FieldFormatException
    Thrown when the input type does not match the format specified in the metadata. I.e. a string is too long.
    LoginException
    Class of exceptions thrown when a user tries to log in and an authentication failure occurs.
    PermissionException
    Thrown when the authenticated SOAP user does not have permission to perform the requested operation
    RequiredFieldException
    Thrown when required data is missing from a bean.
    SOAPException
    A generic SOAP exception.
    SOAPRetryableException
    SOAPRetryableException is the class for all exceptions that are retryable immediately. The primary example of this is ConcurrentDataChangeException.
    SOAPSenderException
    SOAPSenderException is the base class for all exceptions that resulted from a sender error. This usually means that required data was not properly encoded or was absent. Senders should not send the message again unless some steps have been taken to make the encoded data valid.
    SOAPServerException
    SOAPServerException is the base class for all exceptions that resulted from a server error. This is something of a catch-all exception type insofar as some things which might in fact be considered SOAPSenderExceptions are reported as SOAPServerExceptions. Perhaps a rule failed or something else. Generally it indicates a problem in the server that is likely retryable at some future time. The database being down, an unavailable plugin, etc would fall into this catagory.
    ServerStateException
    ServerStateException is thrown when a request is made at a time the server is in a state that disallows the request. An example is if an attempt is made to add a claim and the server is in maintenance mode.
    UnknownTypeKeyException
    Thrown when a typekey value isn't available on the server. This exception can only happen if the SOAP WSDL that is being used on the remote side is invalid.
